    52	
    53	<objective>
    54	Refactor the mzPeak writer so it converts arbitrarily large RAW files in constant memory and survives individual bad scans — WITHOUT changing the v1 point layout, so the work is verifiable against the v1 conformance bar (mzpeak-validate 0/0, identical logical output).
    55	
    56	Two mechanical pillars, both fully specified by RESEARCH.md:
    57	1. Streaming: extend MzPeakParquet with a multi-row-group Open->WriteRowGroup*->(set final metadata)->Close path (verified: one ParquetWriter + N CreateRowGroup() reads back as one logical table). Stream the unbounded DATA facets (spectra_data, spectra_peaks, chromatograms_data) to seekable temp files in bounded row groups (cap 1,048,576 rows), then bounded CopyTo each temp file into its STORED zip entry and delete it. Metadata facets stay buffered (bounded by spectrum count). The seekable temp file is mandatory: a ParquetWriter on a non-seekable stream SILENTLY buffers the whole facet in RAM (no throw) — the trap this plan must structurally prevent. The footer KV (spectrum_count / point counts / chromatogram_tic_source) is only KNOWN at finalize, so the streaming handle must accept final CustomMetadata AFTER the last row group and BEFORE the writer is disposed.
    58	2. Robustness: make each scan all-or-nothing. The current ROB defect is two-fold: (a) points are appended (lines 154-176) BEFORE the metadata record + ordinal++ (223-225), so a mid-scan throw orphans points under an ordinal with no metadata row and reuses that ordinal; (b) `_precursorScanNumbers[filterKey] = scanNumber` (line 190) mutates SHARED precursor-resolution state PRE-commit, so a scan that fails afterward still poisons a later child's parent lookup even though it committed no rows. Fix: stage ALL of a scan's state (data/peaks/metadata rows, precursor/selected_ion, scanNumber->ordinal map, the precursor-map entry, the TIC/chromatogram contribution) locally and apply EVERYTHING only on full success; on failure log + ParseInput.NewError() and skip (nothing applied, ordinal NOT consumed), mirroring MzMlSpectrumWriter.
    59	
    60	Purpose: operational foundation (constant memory + fault tolerance) that the chunked/Numpress phases build on.
    61	Output: extended MzPeakParquet streaming API, refactored MzPeakSpectrumWriter, new NUnit tests, and recorded MEM-02 peak-RSS measurement.
    62	</objective>
