   191	  <name>Task 3: Per-scan all-or-nothing robustness (stage-then-commit, incl. precursor-map)</name>
   192	  <files>ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs, ThermoRawFileParser/ThermoRawFileParserTest/MzPeakWriterTests.cs</files>
   193	  <action>
   194	Fix the ROB defect: make each scan all-or-nothing so a mid-scan throw consumes NO ordinal, leaves NO rows in any facet, and mutates NO shared resolution state. The existing try/catch (142-232) stays; the change is WHERE state mutates.
   195	
   196	- Restructure the per-scan body so ALL reads/builds for a scan land in PER-SCAN LOCAL staging FIRST: a local data point buffer (index/mz/intensity for this scan), a local peaks buffer, the local Record, the local filterKey, and the parent-derivation result — built BEFORE touching ANY shared/streaming state. Move the current early appends (data at 154-159, peaks at 168-176) into these locals using a placeholder; do not write the shared/streaming buffers yet.
   197	- Keep the entire read+build (ReadMZData, OrderedPairs, the profile/centroid peak read, GetScanStatsForScanNumber, ScanTrailer, parent-derivation, BuildPrecursor) inside the try.
   198	- S2 (HIGH — core correctness): the `_precursorScanNumbers[filterKey] = scanNumber` mutation currently at line 190 is SHARED state read by later children's parent lookup (BuildPrecursor -> GetParentFromScanString). It MUST move OUT of the pre-commit position and into the success-only commit block. A scan that throws after computing filterKey must NOT update _precursorScanNumbers, or a later child resolves its precursor through the skipped scan. Compute filterKey into a local during the try; apply `_precursorScanNumbers[filterKey] = scanNumber` ONLY in the success-commit block alongside the other staged state.
   199	- ONLY after the scan fully succeeds (end of try body), in the commit block, apply EVERYTHING atomically: assign the current ordinal to the staged rows; append them to the data/peaks streaming staging buffers (flushing a row group if at RowGroupRowCap); add peakSpectra entry if peaks exist; add the Record; set scanNumberToOrdinal[scanNumber]=ordinal; set _precursorScanNumbers[filterKey]=scanNumber; then ordinal++. (Note: the per-scan TIC/chromatogram contribution is currently gathered post-loop by CaptureTic over `records`, so a skipped scan that produced no Record already contributes no chromatogram point — keep that property; if any chromatogram staging is moved inline, it too commits only on success.)
   200	- On exception: catch -> Log.Error(scan # + message) + Log.Debug(stack) + ParseInput.NewError() (NOT NewWarn — a dropped scan is data loss, matching MzMlSpectrumWriter) -> continue. Because nothing was committed, ordinal is not consumed, no facet got rows, and _precursorScanNumbers is unchanged. Note: the `continue` for filtered scans (level/MsLevel at 146, empty mz at 152) must also commit nothing — preserve as today (those paths must not have touched _precursorScanNumbers either; verify the filterKey/precursor-map write is reached only on the commit path).
   201	- This preserves dense ordinals and spectra_data/spectra_peaks/metadata parity even with skips, composes with row-group flushing (a partially-built scan never reaches a buffer), and guarantees a skipped scan never poisons a later child's parent resolution.
   202	- FAILURE CLASS DISTINCTION (NEW-1): only per-scan READ/BUILD failures (inside the try, before the commit block) are skippable (catch -> NewError -> continue). A failure during the COMMIT block itself — specifically a row-group flush / Parquet write / temp-file I/O error — is NOT a recoverable per-scan skip: bytes may already be partially written, so it must PROPAGATE (fail the conversion) rather than be swallowed as a skipped scan. Structure the try so the commit-block writes (the append/flush path) are outside the skip-catch (or rethrow write/IO exceptions), so a flush failure aborts cleanly instead of silently corrupting output while counting a "skip".
   203	
