    93	## Decisions Block (per unknown)
    94	
    95	### Decision 1 — Parquet.Net 5.0.1 multi-row-group streaming: CONFIRMED
    96	
    97	One `ParquetWriter` can create many row groups sequentially; readers see **one logical table**.
    98	Verified empirically (EXP1): three `CreateRowGroup()` calls on a single writer produced a file with
    99	`RowGroupCount == 3` and 9 total rows read back across the groups; pyarrow independently read 9 rows
   100	/ 3 row groups. `[VERIFIED: ran Parquet.Net 5.0.1 on this machine, /tmp/pqexp]`
   101	
   102	The pattern that mirrors the existing `WriteAsync` body:
   103	
   104	```csharp
   105	// MzPeakParquet streaming path (NEW) — open once, write N row groups, close to flush footer.
   106	// seekableSink MUST be a seekable Stream (temp FileStream). See Decision 3.
   107	public static async Task<ParquetWriter> OpenAsync(Stream seekableSink, ParquetSchema schema,
   108	    IReadOnlyDictionary<string, string> customMetadata)
   109	{
   110	    var writer = await ParquetWriter.CreateAsync(schema, seekableSink).ConfigureAwait(false);
   111	    writer.CompressionMethod = CompressionMethod.Zstd;               // same codec as WriteAsync
   112	    if (customMetadata != null) writer.CustomMetadata = customMetadata;
   113	    return writer;
   114	}
   115	
   116	// Call once per buffer flush. columns carries the SAME (defined, defLevels, repLevels) triples
   117	// the existing Column() chokepoint already builds, just for a buffer-sized slice of rows.
   118	public static async Task WriteRowGroupAsync(ParquetWriter writer, ParquetSchema schema,
   119	    IDictionary<DataField, (Array defined, int[] defLevels, int[] repLevels)> columns)
   120	{
   121	    using (var rg = writer.CreateRowGroup())
   122	        foreach (var field in schema.GetDataFields())
   123	        {
   124	            var t = columns[field];
   125	            await rg.WriteColumnAsync(Column(field, t.defined, t.defLevels, t.repLevels)).ConfigureAwait(false);
   126	        }
   127	}
   128	// Caller disposes the ParquetWriter at end-of-facet → footer flushed to the temp file.
   129	```
   130	
   131	**How the current `WriteAsync` differs (single row group):** `MzPeakParquet.cs:156-175` opens the
   132	writer, creates **exactly one** `CreateRowGroup()`, writes every column once, and disposes. The
   133	minimal extension is to split that into *open* (CreateAsync + codec + metadata) / *write-row-group*
   134	(the inner `CreateRowGroup` loop, callable N times) / *close* (dispose the writer). `WriteAsync`
   135	itself can be left intact for the metadata facets, or trivially re-expressed as Open + one
   136	WriteRowGroup + dispose.
   137	
   138	`CustomMetadata` is set on the writer before the first row group and is written into the single file
   139	footer on dispose — it does **not** need to be repeated per row group. The existing facet KV
   140	metadata (`spectrum_count`, `spectrum_array_index`, etc.) therefore still works unchanged; it is
   141	computed once and attached before close. `[VERIFIED: Parquet.Net source ParquetWriter.cs;
   142	CustomMetadata is a writer-level footer field]`
   143	
   144	**Append-reopen also works** (EXP3): `ParquetWriter.CreateAsync(stream, append: true)` on a
   145	re-opened file adds row groups (RowGroupCount went 1→2). This is the mechanism the existing
   146	`ParquetSpectrumWriter.cs:104-108` uses via the high-level `ParquetSerializer` (`opts.Append=true`).
   147	For this phase prefer the **single open writer** form (Decision 1 snippet) — fewer file reopens,
   148	same result — but append-reopen is a proven fallback. `[VERIFIED: EXP3]`
   149	
   150	### Decision 2 — Seekable target strategy (temp file → STORED zip): VALIDATED
   151	
   152	The temp-file approach is correct **and necessary**. Confirmed (zip-entry test): a multi-row-group
   153	parquet written to a temp `FileStream`, then bounded-`CopyTo`'d (64 KB buffer) into
   154	`zip.CreateEntry(name, CompressionLevel.NoCompression).Open()`, produced an entry with
   155	`CompressedLength == Length == 1560` (STORED) and read back with all 4 row groups intact via
   156	`ParquetReader`. `[VERIFIED: /tmp/pqexp zip-entry test]`
   157	
   158	Gotchas, all confirmed:
   159	- **The zip entry stream is NOT seekable** (`CanSeek == False`, `CanWrite == True`). You can only
   160	  forward-write into it. That is fine for `CopyTo` of bounded buffers, and is exactly why you cannot
   161	  write Parquet *directly* into it (Decision 3). `[VERIFIED: printed CanSeek=False]`
   162	- **STORED requires `CompressionLevel.NoCompression`** — already used by the current
   163	  `AddStored` (`MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:631`). Keep it.
   164	- **`leaveOpen: true`** on the `ZipArchive` ctor is already in use
   165	  (`MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:266`) so the outer `Writer.BaseStream` survives for the final
   166	  `Writer.Flush()/Close()`. Preserve this.
   167	- **Constant memory:** the `CopyTo` reuses one bounded buffer; only ~64 KB is live during the copy
   168	  regardless of facet size.
   169	
   170	**Non-temp-file alternative — REJECTED.** Handing `ParquetWriter` a growable `MemoryStream` keeps the
   171	whole facet in RAM (the v1 behavior we are removing). Handing it the non-seekable zip-entry stream
   172	does **not** error and does **not** stream — it silently buffers the entire facet in an internal
   173	`MemoryStream` and flushes on dispose (forward-only test: 0 seek calls, full data still landed,
   174	447 bytes). So both non-temp routes reintroduce whole-facet memory. There is **no** streaming-direct-
   175	to-zip option in Parquet.Net 5.0.1 because Parquet's footer-at-end format fundamentally needs seek.
   176	**Recommendation: temp file is the approach.** `[VERIFIED: forward-only stream test + official source]`
   177	
   178	### Decision 3 — Does `ParquetWriter` need a SEEKABLE stream? YES (and it fails silent if not)
   179	
   180	The official `ParquetActor` base seeks (`SeekOrigin.Begin`/`End`, `GoBeforeFooterAsync`) — Parquet's
   181	metadata footer sits at the end and references earlier offsets. `[CITED:
   182	github.com/aloneguid/parquet-dotnet ParquetActor.cs]`
   183	
   184	Critical empirical nuance for this codebase: passing a `CanSeek==false` stream does **not** raise.
   185	Parquet.Net 5.0.1 detects non-seekability and wraps it in an internal buffer, writing everything on
   186	dispose (forward-only test: `seekCalls=0`, output valid). **This is a trap** — it would look like
   187	streaming works while actually buffering the whole facet. The plan must therefore assert the sink is a
   188	real seekable `FileStream`, never the zip-entry stream. `[VERIFIED: forward-only stream test]`
   189	
   190	### Decision 4 — Row-group flush cadence
   191	
   192	**Trigger: row count.** Default cap **1,048,576 rows** to match the established
   193	`ParquetSpectrumWriter.cs:41` (`ParquetSliceSize = 1_048_576`) — a known-good value already shipping
   194	in this repo for the same point-row data. Recommend a single named const on `MzPeakSpectrumWriter`
   195	(e.g. `RowGroupRowCap = 1_048_576`) so it is one-line tunable. A bytes-based secondary trigger is
   196	**not needed** for point rows (each row is one (index, mz, intensity) ≈ 20 bytes, so 1M rows ≈ 20 MB
   197	buffered per facet — small and predictable); leave it to Claude's discretion if a future facet has
   198	wide rows. `[VERIFIED: ParquetSpectrumWriter.cs:41,104]`
   199	
   200	**Spectra do NOT need to stay whole within a row group for point layout.** Each row is a single
   201	point carrying its own `spectrum_index`; readers reconstruct a spectrum by selecting all rows with a
   202	given `spectrum_index`, which is correct across row-group boundaries (EXP1 read all rows across 3
   203	groups as one table). So a spectrum's points may freely span row groups. (This is the *opposite* of
   204	`mzparquet`'s row-per-scan-array model where ParquetSpectrumWriter keeps a scan whole — that
   205	constraint does not apply to mzPeak point layout.) Flush whenever the buffer hits the cap, mid-
   206	spectrum is fine. `[VERIFIED: EXP1 cross-group read; point-layout schema MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:640]`
   207	
   208	### Decision 5 — Per-scan robustness pattern + the real S4 root cause
   209	
   210	**Mirror target — `MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:422-433`:**
   211	```csharp
   212	SpectrumType spectrum = null;
   213	int level;
   214	try
   215	{
   216	    level = (int) _rawFile.GetScanEventForScanNumber(scanNumber).MSOrder; //applying MS level pre filter
   217	    if (level <= ParseInput.MaxLevel)
   218	        spectrum = ConstructMSSpectrum(scanNumber);
   219	}
   220	catch (Exception ex)
   221	{
   222	    Log.Error($"Scan #{scanNumber} cannot be processed because of the following exception: {ex.Message}");
   223	    Log.Debug($"{ex.StackTrace}\n{ex.InnerException}");
   224	    ParseInput.NewError();          // count, do NOT rethrow
   225	}
   226	// only on success: assign index, serialize, index++  (MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:437-458)
   227	```
   228	`ParseInput.NewError()` (`ParseInput.cs:161-164`) just increments `_errors`; `NewWarn()`
   229	(`ParseInput.cs:166-169`) increments `_warnings`. Errors are appropriate for a dropped scan (it is a
   230	data loss), matching `MzMlSpectrumWriter`'s use of `NewError()` for the per-scan failure (it reserves
   231	`NewWarn()` for recoverable metadata gaps, e.g. lines 785/1276/1429). Use **`NewError()`** for a
   232	skipped scan.
   233	
   234	**The current MzPeakSpectrumWriter ALREADY has a per-scan try/catch** at
   235	`MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:142-232`, catching at line 227 with `Log.Error(...)` +
   236	`ParseInput.NewError()`. So the gap is **not** a missing try/catch. The actual defect:
   237	
   238	- Points are appended to the shared accumulators **early** — `dataIndex/dataMz/dataIntensity` at
   239	  lines **154-159**, `peaksIndex/...` at lines **168-176** — using the current `ordinal`.
   240	- The metadata `Record` is added at line **223** and `ordinal++` runs at line **225**, both at the
   241	  *end* of the try body, after `GetScanStatsForScanNumber` (179), `ScanTrailer` (180),
   242	  parent-derivation (184-190), and `BuildPrecursor` (217-221).
   243	- If any step in 179-221 throws (the S4_5foldGHRP scan #25081 "Cannot get scan event" / stats class),
   244	  the catch skips the record and does **not** advance `ordinal` — **but the data/peak points already
   245	  pushed at 154-176 remain under that ordinal**. The next good scan reuses the same `ordinal`,
   246	  producing: (a) orphan `spectra_data` points whose `spectrum_index` has no metadata row, and (b) two
   247	  spectra collapsed onto one ordinal. Facet parity (`spectrum_count` == distinct `spectrum_index`)
   248	  breaks. In the streaming design this is worse: orphan points may already have been flushed to a
   249	  row group and cannot be retracted.
   250	
   251	**Required skip semantics (all-or-nothing per scan):**
   252	1. Read + build everything for the scan into **per-scan local staging** (a local point buffer for
   253	   data, one for peaks, a local `Record`) *before* touching any shared accumulator or streaming
   254	   writer.
   255	2. Wrap the entire read+build in the try. On exception → `Log.Error` + `ParseInput.NewError()` +
   256	   `continue`; nothing was staged into shared state, so **no ordinal is consumed and no facet got
   257	   rows**.
   258	3. Only after the scan fully succeeds: assign the current `ordinal` to the staged rows, append them to
   259	   the row-group buffers (flushing if at cap), add the `Record`, then `ordinal++`.
   260	This guarantees dense ordinals and data/metadata/peaks parity even when scans are skipped, and it
   261	composes with row-group flushing because a partially-built scan never reaches a buffer.
   262	
